This year has been difficult and filled with ups and downs, but damn am I so thankful for your love and consistency through it all.

I’m at my happiest when I’m with you and I love doing life and making memories with you.

You inspire me every day, I am so proud of everything that you have accomplished this year, and 🗣️I CANNOT WAIT to celebrate all of the inevitable success that’s coming for you.

You are truly amazing.
I love you.
This holiday season went a little differently than I had planned but it was nothing short of perfect.

There are some big changes happening in my life at the moment. It’s equally as scary and painful as it is exciting and empowering. 

This photo always hits me so different and so much harder than any other photograph I’ve ever taken— especially when I feel overwhelmed or like I can’t handle the weight of what’s going on.

It’s a reminder that whenever I do feel lost, confused, afraid, or alone that in the end the only person that can pull me through it is myself.

I’m thankful that I’m surrounded by friends and family who love and support me, but I also need to remember to love and support myself. 

Over the past few years I have learned that just as there is strength in solidarity, there is also monumental strength in solitude.

Give it time. Remember who you are.

Best friends who chase dreams together stay together.

You are my biggest inspiration and I wouldn’t be where I am today without you. Through it all, you are always there. I am so proud of you. 

The all nighters were worth it.
Feeling good ♥

I’ve been WAITING for this! The game is changing and creating digital art just got a fast pass.
The power that @adobeexpress has condensed into a simple and easy-to-use format still has my jaw on the floor.

There are so many incredible features but the color pallet sampling that it *automatically* does for you while you’re creating something is a life saver.
If you need to create something quickly but don’t want to sacrifice a lot of key features that you’re used to- Adobe Express really did that. Try it out and see for yourself.

“It makes me happy to see you blossom.”

A good friend of mine told me that the other day.

The past couple months have felt quite transformative for me and I have been in my own world a little more recently.

I’ve been putting a lot of my energy back into myself, making sure I’m taking care of myself emotionally, mentally and physically, and ultimately doing what makes me happy— which everyone should be doing.

But when I’m in this mode I’m always full steam ahead and it’s so easy to just keep the momentum and push forward without taking a beat.

When someone drops a “it makes me happy to see you blossom”, it forces me to stop and look back at the progress I’ve made and to be proud of myself.

Friends like this are so important.

The ones that remind you how well you’re doing, that celebrate your successes like it’s happening to them, that tell you what you *need* to hear, and that make you believe that it really is going to be okay. 

Keep those people close man. Let them remind you to be proud of how far you’ve come.

It’s always the simplest portraits that have such a therapeutic affect on me. The detail shots man. 

Sometimes I think back to 2020 and 2021 when I was pumping out content like a machine and I think I burned myself out pretty badly.

But I’m glad it happened because the burn out forced me to stop. 

If you’re creating for social media, it can be tough out here, but when it comes to something you love, remember why you started.

It’s okay to be absent and take breaks— in any area of life.

Tune out the noise, get back to the basics, reset, move forward :)

I’m going through my work from the past couple years and it feels like I’m watching some of it for the first time.

I remember when I was creating these videos, I was so hard on myself man. Constantly changing things, second guessing myself, worrying and doubting if the client is going to like it or not— I was trying so hard to make something “perfect”. 

Now I look at what I made and I’m like damn— you did that.

@lissettecalv would constantly remind me, “they want to work with you because the like YOU and what you create.” And she was right. And that applies to you too.

I think all artists struggle with the ebb and flow of imposter syndrome to some degree. Not feeling like what we create is “good enough”. We are our biggest critic and sometimes we let the critic in us win.

I let that voice win wayyyy too many battles and I would stop sharing my work but listen—if you hear that inner voice is squawking in your ear saying “this isn’t good enough”, babe she’s lying to you and she can exit.

I’m gonna take my own advice here but keep creating and don’t quit. You art is worth sharing and you are good enough. In fact— you’re better than you think.
